<subSubSection pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,260,392]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Originally described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" box="[483,612,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Lasiochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[483,612,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Lasiochilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Author examined specimens of this species and can confirm that it belongs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1871" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" box="[273,356,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Dilasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[273,356,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Dilasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The presence of spines on hindtibiae in this species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1871" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" baseAuthorityName="B. White" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[956,1099,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Dilasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denigrata">
<emphasis box="[956,1099,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">D. denigrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1871" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" baseAuthorityName="B. White" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[1153,1282,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Dilasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="contorta">
<emphasis box="[1153,1282,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">D. contorta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and probably other (from the Old World) may justify regarding them as a new subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter, 1871" authorityName="Reuter" authorityYear="1871" box="[1018,1100,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Dilasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Hemiptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1018,1100,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Dilasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
